Whereas the magnitude of the magnetization vector M in a ferromagnet is always equal to the saturation magnetization MS, its direction can vary internally. The spatial variation can be static, as in a domain wall, or dynamic, as in spin waves. The equation of motion for the magnetization, the so-called LLG equation, was first described by Landau and Lifshitz [51] in 1935 and later cast in a slightly different form by Gilbert [52], who in 1955 introduced a friction-like form for the damping, and a phenomenological damping parameter
. To account for how STT can modify and also drive the magnetodynamics, Slonczewski added a spin torque term in 1996 [1], such that the resulting LLGS equation becomes
@M
@t ¼ ½Heff M þ T þ TS (1)
where the first term describes conservative Larmor precession around an effective field Heff , the second term describes the damping torque, and the last term TS is the Slonczewski spin-transfer torque. Heff can be written as a sum of the externally applied field Ha, the magneto–dipolar field Hdip, an anisotropy field Hk, the exchange field Hex, and, in the presence of a drive current, the Oersted field Hoe
Heff ¼ Ha þ Hdip þHk þHex þ Hoe: (2)
